The main problem was with the canned drinks each time we ordered with the food. Every single time all the canned drinks had past their expiration dates by about 1 to 2 years. The taste of the drinks (mostly diet coke) were awful and the gas has already leaked out. In short, it was like a water with weird taste. It made us wonder about the other canned items that they use for the food (if there is any such as canned beans, etc). I would not have written a comment here if it had happened only once but each time we order canned drinks from Tarascas, we kept receiving awful stuff with past expiration dates, and this is now making us worry about the health standards of the restaurant as well.

Fresh food, Frida Kahlo prints and friendly wait staff make this local spot our go-to Mexican restaurant. Outdoor seating in the summertime is a nice alternative to inside tables on busy (noisy) evenings. (Noise is the reason for four stars instead of five stars.) Mouthwatering selections include grilled jalapeno salmon on a bed of spinach and rice, Cuban quesadillas with shredded beef, sweet plantains, and goat cheese, as well as a fajita combo, large enough to split. Puntas al Albanil (steak tips with bacon,  avocado and rice--yum!) pictured, along with a house margarita and complimentary chips.  Extensive margarita menu draws folks in.   Tarascas serves a delicious weekend brunch as well-- Enjoy!  If you find this review helpful,  please like it-- Thanks! :-)

Been going to Tarascas for the last several years. Their service and atmosphere is fantastic. They are super friendly and on top of drink refills and menu suggestions. Some menu items are better than others. My go-to is the Tarasco burrito suizo style. However, they don't do salads well, and have very limited vegetarian offerings. My biggest gripe is the price point, especially when compared to similar Mexican restaurants in the city. For a casual restaurant, $15+ for a burrito, that's nothing unique, is a bit high in my opinion. In addition, their house margarita is $13, which is nearly double the cost of similar places I've seen. I wish they kept this quality at a more competitive price point. I love going here, especially for their patio and atmosphere, but agree with a lot of the mixed Yelp reviews on price and menu selection. Don't let my mixed feedback deter you from trying it at least once!

Mexican restaurants abound in Chicago.  If you were on a 100% south-of-the-border diet, you need only walk 15 minutes in any direction before happening upon your vittles of choice, even in Lincoln Park.  Quantity does not equal quality though and sometimes you just have to elevate your palate.  If you have an urge to satisfy your Mexican-tooth, try Tarascas, a white tablecloth kinda joint.  Food is good, margs are good, service is good, and the outdoor seating is awesome!  People-watching along Clark: it's time well-spent.
